1310–Deceased","1330–Male":"1330–Deceased","–Male":"Deceased","–Female":"Deceased","1280–1352":"1280–1352","1305":"1305","about 1305":"about 1305","1310":"1310","Abt 1330":"about 1330","1330":"1330","1352":"1352","1308":"1308","1280":"1280","Ruabon, Denbighshire, Wales":"Ruabon, Denbighshire, Wales","Ceidio Rhodogeidio, Anglesey, Wales":"Ceidio Rhodogeidio, Anglesey, Wales","Isle of Anglesey, Wales, United Kingdom":"Anglesey, Wales, United Kingdom","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Adda","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Indian (Punjab): Jat and Sikh habitational name, from Padda village in Gurdaspur district."],"variants":[]},{"name":"Iorwerth","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Traditional: from <i>iōr</i>‘ ‘lord’ + a mutated form of <i>berth</i> ‘handsome’; borne in the <i>Mabinogi</i> by the jealous brother of  Madawg , son of  Maredudd . <i>Iorwerth</i> came to be regarded as a Welsh equivalent of  Edward , but it has no actual connection with that name."],"variants":[{"name":"Yorath","meanings":["Anglicized form of   Iorwerth   or, in some cases, a transferred use of the surname derived from it."]}]},{"name":"ap","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Short form of any of the names beginning with this syllable."],"variants":[{"name":"Alexander","meanings":["From the Latin form of the Greek name <i>Alexandros</i>, from <i>alexein</i> ‘to defend’ + <i>anēr</i> ‘man, warrior’ (genitive <i>andros</i>). The name became extremely popular in the post-classical period, and was borne by several individuals in the New Testament and some early Christian saints. Its use as a common given name throughout Europe, however, derives largely from the fame of  Alexander the Great , King of Macedon (  356–323  bc  ), around whom a large body of popular legend grew up in late antiquity, much of which came to be embodied in the medieval ‘Alexander romances’."]},{"name":"Alan","meanings":["Of Celtic origin and uncertain derivation (possibly a diminutive of a word meaning ‘rock’). It was introduced into England by  Breton  followers of  William the Conqueror , most notably  Alan , Earl of Brittany, who was rewarded for his services with vast estates in the newly conquered kingdom. In Britain the variants  <b>Allan</b>  and  <b>Allen</b>  are considerably less frequent, and generally represent transferred uses of surname forms, whereas in America all three forms of the name are approximately equally common.  See also  Alun ."]},{"name":"Albert","meanings":["From an Old French name, <i>Albert</i>, of Germanic (Frankish) origin, derived from <i>adal</i> ‘noble’ + <i>berht</i> ‘bright, famous’. This was adopted by the Normans and introduced by them to England, displacing the Old English form <i>Æþelbeorht</i>. The name is popular in a variety of forms in Western Europe, and has been traditional in a number of European princely families. It was out of favour in England for centuries, however, and the revival of its popularity in the 19th century was largely in honour of  Queen Victoria's  consort,  Prince Albert of Saxe-Coburg-Gotha ."]}]}],"lifeSummary":"Iorwerth ap Adda was born about 1305, in Ceidio Rhodogeidio, Anglesey, Wales as the son of Adda \" Foel\" ap Einion and Mrs. Adda ap Enion. He married Mrs. Iowerth ap Adda in 1330, in Anglesey, Wales, United Kingdom. They were the parents of at least 2 sons and 1 daughter."},"et":{"about 1305–":"umbes 1305–Surnud","1305–Male":"1305–Surnud","1308–Male":"1308–Surnud","1310–Female":"1310–Surnud","1330–Male":"1330–Surnud","–Male":"Surnud","–Female":"Surnud","1280–1352":"1280–1352","1305":"1305","about 1305":"umbes 1305","1310":"1310","Abt 1330":"umbes 1330","1330":"1330","1352":"1352","1308":"1308","1280":"1280","Ruabon, Denbighshire, Wales":"Ruabon, Denbighshire, Wales","